The repetitions complained of are scarcely to be called repetitions, for they leave out the main point in the previous argument against Plato and the Stoica, viz. the ques- tion as to a creation in time 3 but as far as they are such, they may be explained by the haste and carelessness which characterize the whole treatise, and of which we shall see instances in the latter half of the lst book ; the special difficulty of ἓ 25 is, I think, removed by the explanation given in my note.
